					<span class="label"><a name="footnote7-10711_000_014">7.</a></span>
					<p>&ldquo;A century ago, attachment scholar John Bowlby found that the bond created through the innumerable caring interactions between a mother and child is the critical foundation for social-emotional development. &hellip; And feminist scholar Sara Ruddick identified a mother&rsquo;s &lsquo;attentive love&rsquo; as the core of effective parenting. Through the &lsquo;patient eye of love,&rsquo; mothers develop a special knowledge of their children&mdash;a knowledge that gives them unique insight into what the truly &lsquo;best practices&rsquo; for each child should be&rdquo; (Jenet Jacob Erickson, &ldquo;Love, Not Perfection, Root of Good Mothering,&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Deseret News,</span> May&nbsp;12, 2013, G3).</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="8-10711_000_014"><a name="8-10711_000_014">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote8-10711_000_014">8.</a></span>
					<p>It is true that many women over many generations have been exploited or saddled with unfair burdens both in family and employment, but selflessness and sacrifice need not and should not become abusive or exploitative. Elder Bruce&nbsp;C. Hafen observed: &ldquo;If being &lsquo;selfless&rsquo; means a woman must give up her own inner identity and personal growth, that understanding of selflessness is wrong. &hellip; But today&rsquo;s liberationist model goes too far the other way, stereotyping women as excessively <span class="emphasis">independent</span> of their families. A more sensible view is that husbands and wives are <span class="emphasis">interdependent</span> with each other. &hellip; The critics who moved mothers from dependence to independence skipped the fertile middle ground of interdependence. Those who moved mothers from selflessness to selfishness skipped the fertile middle ground of self-chosen service that contributes toward a woman&rsquo;s personal growth. Because of these excesses, debates about the value of motherhood have, ironically, caused the general society to discount not only mothers but women in general&rdquo; (&ldquo;Motherhood and the Moral Influence of Women&rdquo; [remarks to the World Congress of Families II, Geneva, Plenary Session IV, Nov.&nbsp;16, 1999], http://worldcongress.org/wcf2_spkrs/wcf2_hafen.htm).</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="9-10711_000_014"><a name="9-10711_000_014">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote9-10711_000_014">9.</a></span>
					<p>One mother in a <span class="emphasis">Wall Street Journal</span> editorial observed: &ldquo;With the exception of some Mormons, evangelicals and Orthodox Jews, scads of us don&rsquo;t know how to teach our own sons and daughters not to give away their bodies so readily. &hellip; Still, in my own circle of girlfriends, the desire to push back is strong. I don&rsquo;t know one of them who doesn&rsquo;t have feelings of lingering discomfort regarding her own sexual past. And not one woman I&rsquo;ve ever asked about the subject has said that she wishes she&rsquo;d &lsquo;experimented&rsquo; more&rdquo; (Jennifer Moses, &ldquo;Why Do We Let Them Dress Like That?&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Wall Street Journal,</span> Mar.&nbsp;19, 2011, C3).</p>
